<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=18&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;18</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=20&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;20&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_19.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_19.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>BATMAN '88</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>6 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
This was another game which popped up onto the radar out of nowhere -
perhaps because this wasn't an in-house game, but a game farmed off by
Ocean to splinter group Special FX. There was no fanfare, and didn't
even merit more than a footnote in an unrelated article which casually
mentioned that there were two more <i>Batman</i> games on the way from Ocean
- this, plus the game that was to be based on the 1989 movie.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=250 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d19_1988_pre3.png" target="1988_pre3.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d19_1988_pre3_small.jpg" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=175></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i><i>Batman</i> caught many people by surprise, seeming to come out of nowhere.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>It was Sinclair User who broke the news properly with a preview in
their November issue, and the large comic strip style graphics stood
it out from the crowd. It's perhaps a reflection of Ocean's stature by
that time that <i>Batman: The Caped Crusader</i> was felt to not merit the
usual pre-Christmas hype, outshone as it was by <i>Operation Wolf</i>,
<i>Robocop</i>, <i>Rambo III</i> and <i>Dragonninja</i> - an embarrassment of riches!
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=250 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d19_1988_rev4.png" target="1988_rev4.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d19_1988_rev4_small.jpg" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=179></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>The impossible-to-OCR YS review raved about this very imaginative game.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>But I'm sure it wasn't the Spectrum version which initially caught my
interest. My strongest memory of the time is seeing large blue-suited
sprites from the 16-bit Amiga and Atari ST versions in the multiformat
mags, but for the life of me I cannot find those articles again, which
is very odd. I'm sure it as after seeing those flashy graphics that I
started to take great interest in this game.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/aFBv-jQhcLw&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/aFBv-jQhcLw&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Crash Batman '88 Demo</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Spot the Catwoman... <b><i>(4:52)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aFBv-jQhcLw" target="aFBv-jQhcLw">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
It was the playable demo that appeared on the January issue of Crash
which cemented itself into my wish list as it contained a large part
of the playing area of the first of the games on the tape. And
although the demo playing area was small (and featured an
eventually-unused Catwoman sprite), it was actually a small portion of
the final game. But the demo showed enough crisp graphics, comic book
action and puzzles to make me want it instantly.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;When I got it, it was one the my first tastes of the massive card
boxes the full-pricers where starting to experiment with. It showed
off the artwork perfectly, but you couldn't help wondering if it
screwed over the shops slightly as they'd take up more space on their
shelves. It didn't really need it, although the free poster was rather
nice - Bob Wakelin is one of the few Spectrum game artwork artists who
people still remember, and the <i>Batman</i> artwork is a good example of
why.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The magazines naturally lapped the game up - a large challenging
arcade adventure with plenty of action usually goes down well - and to
this day it draws top marks in reviews from both magazines and fans
alike.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR><TR><TD><IMG SRC="chocs/voxpop.png" ALIGN="LEFT"><br><IMG SRC="pngs/joffasmifff.jpg" ALIGN="RIGHT"><TABLE BACKGROUND="/black7.png"><TR><TD><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#ffff00"><B><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;JONATHAN SMITH&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><br>
<b>Joffa here is one of the leading Spectrum programmers from way-back-when, producing top-notch titles for Ocean, including <i>Batman: Caped Crusader</i>. Over to you Jof...</b><br><br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Who are you and what are you up to?</font></i></b><br>
 My real name is Jonathan Smith, but everyone but familly call me 'Joff'. 'Joff' or 'Joffa' is a nick name given to anybody called Jonathan around the Liverpool area. I know of two other 'Joffas' within a mile radius of where I live.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I prefer to spell it as 'Jof' because I can do more things with it graphically.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite cracker gift (aside from fortune-telling fish, naturally)?</font></i></b><br>
What? I got one of those whistle type things that have a curled up paper tube thing that unfurles like a snake and squeeks when blown.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; My then 3 year old nephew had never experienced this before and I freaked his little face off.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Why I am writting about cracker gifts?
<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=150 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d19_batmanad.jpg" target="batmanad.jpg"><IMG SRC="pngs/d19_batmanad_small.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=210></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>The Batman ad - and I spy blue-suited sprites... very cartoony, and that put the Speccy version up onto my radar.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/sDeGQfroApM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/sDeGQfroApM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Hamlet Christmas Turkey Advert (1989)</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Bet you're humming along with it at the end... <b><i>(0:31)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sDeGQfroApM" target="sDeGQfroApM">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Christmas Song?</font></i></b><br>
Frosty the Snowman (Steve Nelson and Walter Rollins) by 'The Ronettes'.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best memory of Christmases gone by?</font></i></b><br>
Hmmm. Getting an Atari VCS and a <i>Missile Command</i> cartridge two days before Xmas day and being allowed to play with it.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I got it from the local Woolworths and just before getting to the check-out there was a bomb scare and everyone had to exit the store till the police arrived and let everyone back in.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best Speccy Christmas memory?</font></i></b><br>
Oh, none. Showing my age now! I don't really ever remember getting, or buying, anything Speccy releated at Xmas time. I was too old!
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Quality Street chocolate?</font></i></b><br>
I'd have to say the "Green Triangle". I'm not really into chocolate that much. I bought about &pound;40 worth of retro and foreign stuff a while back and it is all still there!
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/tSJMSnj6UUM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/tSJMSnj6UUM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Step Into Christmas / Elton John</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Relentlessly cheerful! <b><i>(5:37)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tSJMSnj6UUM" target="tSJMSnj6UUM">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best present ever?</font></i></b><br>
A Super 8mm Cine Camera with a single frame animation feature. It was a combined Xmas / birthday present and I had to wait a while to be able to buy a second-hand projector.
It cost about &pound;15 (circa 1980) for 3 minutes and 20 seconds of film (100 feet), and you had to wait two weeks to get the stuff you had shot developed.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Speccy game you most looked forward to?</font></i></b><br>
I honestly can't think of any game, Spectrum or otherwise, that I have looked forward to.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sure, there have been games that have popped up that have really impressed me, and if anybody wants to send me some I'll be more than happy!
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Working for Ocean (whom part owned Centre Soft Distribution along with US Gold) meant that I got to see games from other companies before they were released to the public.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Before my software employment I knew a guy in the local computer shop (the shop was called 'The Computer Shop') and got to see pre-production versions of games like <i>Jet Set Willy</i> before their release.
</TD></TR>
</TABLE><p>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
</TD><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
